Barack Obama will be the fourth U.S. president to receive the Nobel Peace Prize
U.S. President Barack Obama will arrive in Oslo, Norway to spend 26 hours and receive the Nobel Peace Prize, as the fourth U.S. president in history.
The diploma, medal and check of $1.4 million will receive them, among other things, for the exceptional effort in strengthening world diplomacy and cooperation among nations.
The head of the White House and his wife Michelle will arrive in the Norwegian metropolis in the morning and they will have a lot to do.
First, visit the Nobel Institute, where for the first time he will meet the five members of the committee that elected him from 172 people and 33 organizations in October.
Afterwards, the presidential couple plans a meeting with the King of Norway, Harald V, and Queen Sonia.
In the afternoon, the visit will culminate with a ceremony at which Obama will receive the prestigious award.
He will be the fourth U.S. president to receive him, though the third to receive him in office.
The White House has already announced that, upon receiving the award, it will talk about the Afghan war.
The President does not want to avoid this issue, knowing that he is receiving the award as president of a country that is currently at war in two countries.
Their war efforts increased even more with the sending of additional troops to Afghanistan, which does not forget to mention any of its critics.
At the ceremony, Obama will also receive the gold medal, diploma and check of ten million Swedish kronor (approximately 24 million Czech kronor).
It proposes to donate them for charitable purposes, but it has not yet decided to which specific organization.
During his full program, the President and his wife will participate in a banquet attended by the Norwegian kings, the prime minister and 250 other guests.
Obama had a rather reserved attitude toward the award from the beginning.
He mentioned, for example, having the feeling of not deserving it at all.
He also repeated several times that the prize is not only for him, but for all those who fight for the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement he mentioned that it represents “a challenge to take action.”
