USA: Repetition is the Mother of Wisdom
It is comical that Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of the smartest man, as a diligent student repeats in the Afghan question the strategy of his predecessor, whom he himself took for the dumbest.
When he finally revealed his Afghan approach, eagerly awaited, it was shown to be a copy of the script used for Iraq by Bush, created three years ago.
Not only does the same text repeatedly use the phrase “as in Iraq,” but it also did not hesitate to use the title of Bush’s January 2007 statement for its own statement: “A new way forward.”
It was he himself who three years ago criticized Bush’s idea of sending new military reinforcements to Iraq, the country suffering from the civil war, and that criticized it as “an irresponsible decision with catastrophic consequences.”
The following months, however, showed that Bush’s strategy, based on the recommendations of field captains, was the only possible and successful one, so that today nothing is said about Iraq in the news.
Bush's reputation did not improve, however objectively left his successor with a much more favorable initial situation than might have been expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes the miracle will happen again.
The field captains again asked him to increase the military contingent, especially the commander-in-chief of the Afghan operation General Stanley McCristal, who, even despite traditional subordinate relations, subjected the undecided riflemen in the White House to harsh criticism.
He asked 40,000 men to improve the situation.
The president hesitated for three months, but nothing better occurred to him, so he at least deceived the general about 10,000 military personnel.
He managed to get Europe to promise him another 5,000, although he himself previously had at least 10,000.
The most problematic part of Obama’s entire strategy seems to be his goal, to start withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and to finish this procedure in three years.
Many doubt that the increase will bear the same fruit as the procedure in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars in recent years, Iraq’s society is relatively well organized, its leaders respect the agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan is different: no one can be trusted and no agreement is reached.
Under these conditions it is difficult to prepare the Afghan security forces, if they are used to changing the boss every day according to their needs.
Political institutions, although formally established, will remain only a people of Potemkin, and patriarchal tribal relations will remain behind.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extraordinarily complicated because of confusing relationships, even more complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Not even establishing a state that is “actionable,” a minimal goal of the entire operation, seems very real.
The horizon of Obama’s strategy is shocking because of his voluntarism.
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has continued to worsen and is now about to erupt.
Only a romantic soul, who knows nothing of reality, can believe that the military sent to war to "come home soon", will do some miracle here.
From a political point of view, setting a date for the withdrawal of troops is pure irresponsibility, as the Taliban will consider it an indirect declaration of American defeat.
The latest NATO summit showed that Europeans are less and less willing to participate in military operations in Afghanistan.
European politicians do not know, nor do they want to explain to their voters, what the security of Germany or Italy has to do with the war with Hindu Kush.
The other factor, capable of radically affecting the situation, is the development of events in Iran.
If the situation continues to get worse and the increased sanctions have no effect on the Iranians, the US will have to make a difficult decision: try to solve the problem with military force or not.
It will be necessary to look for the answers precisely when, according to Obama, America initiates the triumphal withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan.
However, each such solution will mean a dramatic setback for the Afghan situation.
The only positive for Barack Obama is the fact that the presidential election is three years away and that’s why there’s still plenty of time to find another strategy, if it turns out to be a total failure.
