The secret of splendor over Norway solved: the Russians made tests of a missile
A special luminous effect of unknown origin was observed on Norway.
Russia’s defense ministry said it had tested a ballistic intercontinental missile near the border with Norway.
The missile, of the “Bulava” type, previously intended to be the pride of the Russian army, is becoming the nightmare of Russian generals and Prime Minister Vladimir Putin.
Not even his repeated presence in the missile tests has had the desired effect on the success of the test flights.
Bulava, in most cases, did not fly out or there was a failure in the air.
In Russian newspapers they write of "Bulava" as "a missile that does not fly".
A missile that does not fly, but shines.
During the 13th test, there was no problem at first.
At the end of the flight, there were technical problems with the aircraft.
The engine probably exploded in the third stage of the missile.
This time "Bulava" was launched from the nuclear submarine Dmitry Donskoy, which floated submerged in the White Sea.
This type of missile makes it possible to launch from a vessel that is moving and is submerged at the same time.
That’s why it’s likely that the mysterious light over Norway, caused by an unidentified flying object, was actually the failed “Bulava.”
The Norwegians likewise from the first moment did not hesitate that it was a Russian missile.
The generals this time defend themselves by saying that you can’t just talk about a failure.
The first two stages of the missile endured and the failure occurred in the third.
In the previous cases the engines broke down immediately in the first stage.
Although none of the launches went completely error-free, according to the Ministry of Defense management only six of the thirteen were unsuccessful.
The success of almost fifty percent is full of optimism to the generals and that is why they continue to claim that "Bulava" will one day fly smoothly and that it will even manage to carry up to ten nuclear hypersonic blocks, whose maximum total weight is 1.15 tons.
