A UN group outlines a plan to reduce emissions
The UN-sponsored climate conference, characterized so far by defiant postures and mutual recriminations, grabbed renewed attention on Friday with the release of a document that envisions ambitious greenhouse gas reductions over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations carrying most of the burden on their shoulders in the short term.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles and highlighted the way forward.
But it was seen as a major breakthrough in a negotiation that is running out of time, with more than 100 world leaders coming to Copenhagen next week.
Developed by an ad hoc UN working group, the text does not talk about how much money rich countries would give the poor to cope with global warming in the short and long term.
And this offers a variety of options for key questions, including how developed economies and major emerging economies would cut their coal production, and what the limit of the global temperature rise that political strategists would be willing to tolerate would be.
This gives the process a lot of flexibility, said John Coequyt, a senior representative in Washington for the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the six-page document, summarized a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN’s top climate official, Yvo de Boer, described as “the big picture.”
It shows the profiles for a possible agreement, in which industrialized nations would collectively cut their emissions by 25 to 45 percent by 2020, compared to 1990 levels, while major developing countries would reduce their emissions over the same period by 15 to 30 percent.
Together, countries would cut emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union also spurred talks on Friday, vowing to provide $3.6 billion annually over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to the impact of climate change, from floods and droughts to deforestation.
However, Friday was the same kind of verbal fireworks that dominated the conversations last week.
U.S. special climate envoy Todd Stern rejected claims calling for mandatory greenhouse gas emissions cuts for industrialized countries, compared to volunteers from major emerging economies, if they were not financed by the developed world.
The manoeuvre indicated that the Obama administration is taking a harder line with China, compared to what Bush administration officials did just two years ago.
The United States will not make a deal without major developing countries moving forward and taking action, Stern said, adding that the text did not do enough to ensure the cuts could be verified by outside observers.
Stern made his remarks an hour after Chinese Deputy Foreign Minister He Yafei said the top U.S. climate negotiator lacked “common sense,” or was “very irresponsible” for saying earlier in the week that the U.S. would not help China economically cope with global overheating.
With the future economic trajectory of the world’s major powers at stake, fault lines have erupted both within the developing world and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is both to save individual economies and to save the planet, with China and the United States facing off on their respective obligations, while poorer nations insist that the world’s 24 most influential countries are ignoring the scientific imperative to take the most courageous action.
Ricardo Ulate, a Costa Rican delegate, said it’s not surprising that major powers are arguing over who should pay for spending to limit greenhouse gases, even as vulnerable countries have become more aggressive in trying to hold large issuers accountable for their actions.
This is clearly a game where a new economic hegemony is developing, said Ulate, who also works as a regional advisor on climate change in Mexico and Central America, for Conservation International.
Some of the countries most vulnerable to the impact of climate change indicated that they would continue to push for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most major participants say the talks will ultimately produce a political agreement.
The 43-member Alliance of Small Island States drafted a 24-page preliminary treaty proposal early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who leads international climate negotiations on behalf of the European Commission, said pushing small island nations has “put political pressure on the entire political process,” in part because they are now unified and demanding action from emerging economies such as China and India.
The talks took on a new urgency as delegates focused on the fact that they must resolve most of the exceptional issues before heads of government come to terms.
Senior officials, such as Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and China’s vice minister, got off the planes and rushed into the halls of the Bella Center, to closed-door meetings and press conferences, to be able to delimit claims to be arbitrated over the next week.
The absolute disorder of the meeting (where every day 13,000 people enter and leave the convention center, the activists who play the guitar present nightly shows mocking the countries that they say are being sold, and preliminary proposals are passed hand-in-hand instead of via mail), poses a challenge.
Intensity just builds: Almost all the key ministers are here right now, and on Wednesday 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
We are entering the major leagues, said Carlos Manuel Rodríguez, vice president for global conservation policy.
The heavyweights are coming.
