Management revolution or the end of business intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of large French companies, our struggle for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain.
More than ten years ago, the attitude of the management of large companies with respect to their employees reminds us of the position of companies with respect to consumers before the marketing revolution: it is about employees adhering to "values" determined from above as before it was about imposing products designed by factory technicians on consumers.
By putting the customer at the center of the company, the marketing revolution gave way to the strategies of conquering the markets... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that have no relation to the customer’s preference factors is repeated regularly.
A demobilization of employees can end in a deadly demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the tip of the iceberg of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, especially R&D and, even more so, business intelligence.
Indeed, BI (Business Intelligence) "requires all parties involved ... to conduct themselves proactively and have a forward-looking outlook"; it requires employees to commit themselves to a commitment that is completely opposed to the recommendations of an authoritarian leadership.
For this reason, we called for a managerial revolution, which would consist of putting employees at the center of the company’s concerns as well as the customer.
Internal opinion polls have a relative utility
Will internal opinion polls, such as the questionnaire conducted by Orange among its employees, incite a managerial revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
-In principle, because I could verify that, faced with a new situation, and after many laps, all the companies end up doing essentially... what they always did! B989
Secondly, because authoritarianism, one of the pathologies of power, grows in proportion to the importance of its own failures.
- Lastly, because most managers have a simplistic view of human behavior.
As they come from the great schools of engineers, they interpret psychology in a mechanistic way.
They adopt, for intellectual convenience, the old behaviorist theory that American “neurosciences” recently revived, and that the Institutes of Studies and the media widely spread behind their backs.
In this way, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the "commands" (sic) of executive engagement, a recent Ipsos research published on Le Figaro.fr reaffirms managers in a mechanistic management posture, unsuitable to today's world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern companies involves adopting a finalist vision of human behavior.
It consists of integrating into any business management reasoning or practice, a fundamental fact: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it clearly appears as a means to make a reality part of their dreams, ambitions and projects.
Today, only studies from Motif Functional Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
Studies have shown that they judge their company based on a predetermined doxa that allows them, through their image of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their own life projects.
Through the identification and measurement of mobilisation factors, business managers can monitor, predict and anticipate their "social performance" and relocate human resource management "in place".
In this way, they create a favorable ground for the organized development of a strong and effective business intelligence.
Oslo speech: for the "fair war" Obama receives praise from the right
On Friday, the American right, pleased that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize has defended the concept of “just war” against America’s enemies, hailed Obama’s speech on Thursday.
Conservatives, who had discredited the award’s handover to Obama on Oct. 9, this time applauded the presidential speech, as did Sarah Palin, a former vice presidential candidate during the 2008 election.
I loved what she said, said Mrs. Palin, a leading figure in the right wing of the Republican Party, to USA Today, adding that she herself had addressed the “sometimes necessary” issue of war in her recently published memoirs.
In my opinion, war is, of course, the last thing Americans want to be forced to do, but it is necessary.
Terrorists must be stopped, he said.
Obama, who inherited the two wars from his predecessor George W. Bush in Iraq and Afghanistan, devoted himself Thursday in Oslo to justifying the use of force, a way to explain his decision to send 30,000 more troops to Afghanistan nine days earlier.
Another opponent of Obama, Newt Gingrich, considered that the president had done "a very good job" in Oslo.
I think the speech was really good, the former speaker of the House of Representatives rejoiced, who appreciated in particular the mention of “the existence of evil in the world” in the presidential words.
At times, the speech seemed very historic to me, Gingrich said, during an interview on the radio show “The Takeaway.”
The former elected representative, whom some consider a potential Republican inauguration candidate for the 2012 presidential election, was pleased to hear “a leftist president” reminding Nobel Committee members “that they would not be free and could not deliver a peace prize if the use of force did not exist.”
According to Michael Gerson, author of George W. Bush’s speeches and current Washington Post columnist, Obama delivered “a very American speech.”
In addition to presenting himself as a “citizen of the world,” as he “always does,” he “spoke like an American president” by reminding Europeans “that they live in a security bubble that they didn’t create and that they don’t do much to preserve it,” Gerson said.
Among the unconvinced right-wing few, a Bush-era hawk, former U.N. ambassador John Bolton, called the speech "monotonous, pretentious and uninspired" on the National Review Online website.
To the president’s left, Democratic Rep. Dennis Kucinich was alarmed to see Barack Obama justifying the use of force.
When we cover war with the notion of justice, it is easy to justify the slaughter of innocents, he warned.
However, the center-left press praised the president.
Los Angeles Time, while still believing that Obama received the Nobel Prize prematurely, called his speech "super-production" especially for a speaker known for his talent.
The Oslo speech “should serve as a roadmap to guide international decisions in the fight against conflict, poverty and oppression,” the newspaper said enthusiastically.
Obama “pronounced the speech that was necessary,” the New York Times said, judging him “at once bleak and uplifting.”
Road transport: three marathon negotiations to ensure Christmas supply
After three sessions of marathon negotiations, the road trade unions and the TLF (Transport and Logistics of France), the only employers' organization that remained until the end, reached an agreement on Friday afternoon that ends the slogan of strike and the threat that falls on the Christmas supply.
During the signing session on Friday night, Transportation Secretary Dominique Bussereau “rejoiced” over the deal, following several negotiating sessions that began Wednesday morning.
After a second night of discussions, negotiators said goodbye at dawn on Friday in the hopes of quickly signing the agreement text late in the morning.
Even though three employer organizations (FNTR, Unostra, OTRE) withdrew giving a door.
But a more than six-hour meeting that began at 11 a.m. was necessary for everyone to agree and the text to be signed at 6 p.m.
The conflict “would have been very damaging to businesses” and “was feared to disrupt the holiday season,” Bussereau said.
The text foresees a 4% increase for the lowest wages (in local and regional road transport), and 2.9% for the highest (international transport).
The hourly rate goes up from 8.72 euros to 9.06 for low wages.
It’s not much, but we started with a lot of disadvantage, explained Patrice Clos (FO).
If so, we will give the order to our militants that there be no more cuts or blockades in the supply centers.
But there may always be some disgruntled rebels, he added.
Philippe Grillot, president of the TLF, acknowledged that this is "a good deal", although it was "difficult to grant increases to high wages in view of international competition".
According to him, the increases will be in the order of 170 euros per month for low wages and 100 to 120 euros for the highest.
It’s a common-sense deal that respects wage earners, Maxime Dumont (CFDT) said, while Thierry Douine (CFTC) recognized it as “a historic deal.”
For Richard Jaubert (CGT) it is “an acceptable compromise.”
The agreement also foresees an increase in travel costs of 3% and the holding of general assemblies of road transport in the first half of 2010, which will mainly allow to address the issue of an extraordinary payment and a modernization of the collective agreement.
Bussereau recalled that "a decrease of 100 million euros in employers' burdens" was the subject of a government amendment to the 2009 rectification finance bill, which the National Assembly voted on Thursday night.
The government will ask the Senate to vote “on the same terms.”
The TLF signature allows the agreement to apply, firstly, to companies that are members of this organization and, secondly, to the entire profession, in case the Minister of Labour makes an extension.
It will be done “as soon as possible,” Bussereau said.
Opposition from employers’ organizations could only delay the process.
The FNTR denounced that it was a "naive business", since the 100 million euros "had already been promised to the sector to offset part of the CO2 tax".
The Secretary of State for Transport forced us to negotiate in an emergency situation, not as a conclusion to an analysis discussed by the parties, but so as not to upset those who wish to eat turkey at the next Christmas dinner, Unostra lamented.
The agreement puts “the stability of many SMEs in the sector during the next 12 months” at risk.
RER A: conflicts over the weekend, unions disagree with the proposals of the RATP
Conflicts on RER A, France’s largest urban public transport line, will continue over the weekend, because at Friday’s meeting, the 2nd day of strike between unions and the RATP leadership, there was no agreement and the unions were dissatisfied with their request for the premium.
For this important holiday shopping weekend, on Saturdays and Sundays trains will only run between 10 a.m. and 8 p.m., with one train out of every two on the central stretch (between La Défense and Nation) and one train out of every four on the other lines.
Interconnection with the SNFC will be suspended in Nanterre Prefecture, forcing passengers to change trains.
The Lafayette Galleries, which expect 200,000 customers each day, were pleased that “RATP strives to serve large stores.”
The RER A crosses the Parisian city from West to East.
The RATP section runs from Saint-Germain-en-Laye and Nanterre to Boissy-Saint-Léger and Marne-La-Vallée.
On Friday, about one in two trains operated at peak hours, and almost no trains operated at valley hours, as had been planned.
On Thursday there was no disorder on the platforms thanks to the organization of the inhabitants of the Island of France.
In this way, at dawn, the station of Saint-Germain-en-Laye (Yvelines) was much less crowded than usual, mainly due to the absence of students.
In Boissy-Saint-Léger (Val-de-Marne), Jack Nbakina, a 29-year-old engineer, explained that he had risen “an hour and a half earlier to arrive on time.”
Saint-Lazare station was not saturated, said the SNCF, which had provided for the supervision of police and law enforcement.
The RER As operated by the SNCF from or to Cergy-Le-Haut arrived or departed from Saint-Lazare station to join the metros.
New general assemblies of striking workers will take place on Saturday and Sunday. The results will be analyzed, "unsatisfactory" according to the unions, of a meeting that was held with the management on Friday afternoon.
The director of the RERs proposes to negotiate a specific protocol in all aspects for the RER A: working time, professional development, etc.
That’s not what drivers who claim a premium owed to them want, according to Thierry Garon (South).
The RATP even puts its premium proposals in parentheses, the CGT said indignantly, noting that the management "was not able to solve a problem that the SNCF and the road sector had already solved".
A new meeting is planned on Monday to conduct "a more extensive analysis on the conditions of exercise of the profession," the RATP said.
Which also led unions to say the company “didn’t care about weekend users.”
In the morning, about 150 drivers stormed a committee at the headquarters in Paris.
Then the management, who until then had refused to dialogue during the strike, suggested the meeting “to calm the waters.”
The conflict could spread to RER B on Tuesday, after Unsa and the Independents filed a notice.
The unions ask for a premium of 120 euros (Unsa) to 150 euros, of which 30 euros are variable (CGT, FO, CFDT, Sud, Indépendants) and complain about the degradation of working conditions on this line that has a million passengers daily.
The drivers of RER, all in the second degree of their professional career, charge from 2,200 to 2,700 euros gross and from 600 to 650 euros of premiums, for hours with alternating shifts, Sundays and holidays.
Turkish judiciary dissolves pro-Kurdish party, a decision with serious consequences
The Turkish Constitutional Court ruled on Friday in favor of the dissolution of the country's main pro-Kurdish party, a decision that immediately sparked angry demonstrations in the Kurdish community, in the southeast of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision could greatly complicate the task of the government, which has just extended a hand to the Kurdish community trying to end 25 years of conflict.
The Democratic Society (DTP) party was dissolved because it had become the “focus of activities that undermined the independence of the state and its indivisible unity,” Court President Hasim Kiliç told reporters after four days of deliberations.
The decision by the 11 judges was unanimous, although it only took a seven-vote majority to get the dissolution, Kiliç said, adding that 37 of the party's leaders, including its president Ahmet Türk and MP Aysel Tugluk, are separated from political life for five years.
The judge also announced the cessation of the parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Türk and Tugluk, and the confiscation of the party’s assets by the Treasury.
The DTP has 21 seats in Parliament (out of 550).
Its leaders warned before the verdict that deputies would leave parliament before being parliamentarians without a party label.
The decision follows a procedure launched by Supreme Court prosecutor Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya in 2007, which accuses the DTP of obeying the “principles” of the Kurdistan Workers’ Party (PKK), considered a terrorist organization by Ankara and many other countries.
Numerous observers believe that the DTP is the legal political showcase of the PKK rebels.
However, the party claims it has no “organic ties” to the PKK, but refuses to qualify it as a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The court’s verdict comes as the government lends a hand to the Kurdish community by proposing a series of measures to strengthen their rights, so that the Kurds stop supporting the PKK and thus end the conflict.
DTP leaders said a dissolution could lead to heightened tensions in Southeast Anatolia, where a large number of demonstrations against the detention conditions of PKK chief Abdullah Öcalan have degenerated into clashes with police in recent weeks.
Since the announcement of justice, thousands of protesters have gathered in front of the DTP premises in Diyarbakir, the large southeastern city mostly populated by Kurds.
Law enforcement threw tear gas grenades and used water cannons, while protesters threw Molotov bombs or sledged stones.
In Istanbul, about a hundred people were also concentrated.
After the verdict, Türk said the court’s decision would “deepen the discouragement.”
Turkey cannot resolve this issue by dissolving a party, he told reporters.
The government, made up of a party from the Islamist movement, also regrets the decision.
In principle, we oppose the closure of parties.
That way nothing is solved, said Energy Minister Taner Yildiz.
This decision completely boycotts the democratic openness launched by the government, commented political analyst Ahmet Insel.
We can expect, of course, a reaction from the PKK, he added.
On Thursday, the PKK claimed responsibility for an attack in which seven soldiers were killed three days earlier in northern Turkey, one of the bloodiest attacks in recent months.
Snow can start suddenly.
A truly cool winter is what Wolfgang Brauburger wants.
It is not something with which you want to make life impossible for citizens, says the director of road maintenance in winter of the EDF
But with it, your employees can learn to test and master the entire vehicle technology.
This weekend, meteorologists may be announcing it for the first time.
More than 330 employees and 120 vehicles are ready to take care of the snow and ice.
In this case, the EDF shall act in accordance with a detailed plan.
As soon as it snows profusely in Frankfurt and temperatures drop below zero degrees, 20 of the so-called A stretches come out with large salted vehicles, explains Brauburger.
These include, for example, major arteries and avenues such as the Neue Weg and the Hanauer Landstraße.
But also the accesses for the fire department, public transport routes, pedestrian areas and sloped sections, such as the Atzelbergstraße.
EDF service starts around three in the morning
They should be covered approximately 1,040 kilometers, as needed, in a maximum of three hours with wet salt, which adheres better.
That’s why the FES starts around three o’clock in the morning, “with it the tracks are free until rush hour traffic begins”.
The hard part is when it starts to snow around 7:30 a.m.
“Then we have a problem,” says the director of winter road maintenance, “because then no one is ready to clear space for salted vehicles.”
Immediately after, when it is no longer snowing, it is up to the secondary and private roads, to which the Rat-Beil-Straße also belongs.
The last priority is the side and side streets.
That's where the inconvenience comes in, Brauburger knows.
Around five o'clock in the morning the FES infantry is launched, mainly dangerous spots and cruise ships are cleared.
Generally, the EDF would not be able to take over all the bike lanes.
In Frankfurt there is a special service, which from 10 p.m. to 4:30 p.m. does not lose sight mainly of the bridges, says Brauburger.
As these become slippery quickly, the salted vehicle starts as soon as the temperature drops below two degrees.
In case of emergency, the police can also call them.
The cradle of the dinosaur
The Tawa trocae looked the same as many other carnivorous dinosaurs: a two-metre-long, 1.50-metre-high animal that ran on both strong hind legs, had an elongated head with sharp and curved teeth, short arms with sickle-shaped claws, and a long tail.
If the species had lived a couple of million years later, it would not have been something special.
But the Tawa juntae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues in Thursday's Science magazine.
The species lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which at the time was in a dry area of the supercontinent Pangea on the equator.
Tawa opened a new window into the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It shows us a lot about the genealogical relationships, propagation and characteristics of the first dinosaurs.
Nesbitt and other paleontologists began an excavation at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico in 2006.
Sometimes, we have found in a day a dozen dinosaur bones, this is something unprecedented for Triassic sediments, reports Randall Irmis, a team member at the Utah Museum of Natural History.
The researchers quickly identified some bones as belonging to a new species.
In the course of the excavation, the remains of five specimens were collected in total.
Finding confirms theories about ancient dinosaur history
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt, it is an exceptional finding: "Triassic dinosaur fossils are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not share such enthusiasm at all.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to current opinion, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
But many of the older fossils are incomplete, so the classification of these early dinosaurs is quite controversial.
Thus, experts debate, for example, when the saurians were divided into their three most important genealogical lineages: the carnivorous theropods among which are the Tyrannosaurus Rex, the Velociraptor and also the birds, the quadruped sauropods known as "long-necked" and their relatives, and the Ornithisauer to herbi.
According to the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa trocae is a primitive theropod.
It shows an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, says Nesbitt.
For example, in the skull of Tawa researchers found evidence of air pockets, such as those also possessed by theropod descendants, birds.
Thanks to air bags, birds breathe more efficiently than mammals.
In the case of Tawa also the bones of the spine were evidently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive airbaged theropod, Randall Irmis says.
Because the related line of later giant sauropods also possessed air bags and light bones, it was likely that the common ancestors of both groups already produced this useful innovation.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs so far known lived in South America, researchers infer that saurians first emerged there.
Consequently, the three genealogical lineages were separated at first and spread from South America to all corners of the Earth, which at that time still formed a single land mass, the supercontinent Pangaea.
However, facts say the team found along with Tawa the remains of two other theropods not closely related.
All three cannot be descended from a single related ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe there were at least three waves migrating to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of the Science study.
Of course, there are also opponents.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in present-day Poland, comments Bonn-Martin Sander paleontologist.
Their opinion could give a distorted image, because simply in South America many dinosaur fossils are still preserved, while in other continents there is hardly anything to discover.
The question of how dinosaurs managed to evolve from a relatively rare collateral line of reptiles to Mesozoic dominant land vertebrates remains an enigma.
Meanwhile, in the Triassic, dinosaurs still shared their living space with many other reptiles, for example, with the ancestors of current crocodiles and pterosaurs and with many other saurians.
Towards the end of the Triassic, dinosaurs expanded across the world and many new species developed, while kinship became extinct at the Triassic boundary to the Jurassic.
Success stories were not eternal.
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
It could have been a mass extinction that dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted, so they were able to beat the opponents in the area.
Successful stories are not always eternal.
150 million years later, a meteor impact brakes the rise of a group of species, which had also evolved in the Triassic and since then had a miserable existence: mammals.
Solidarity from Vienna to Sao Paulo
The list is long and the international signatories.
Participants include professors from the University of Toronto, Cambridge, Vienna or Berkeley, California.
Teachers from Naples, Quebec, Edinburgh, New York, Sao Paulo, Berlin or Bremen participate.
The police eviction of the busy Goethe University casino in Frankfurt has reverberated around the world.
278 professors and professors from Goethe University, but also from higher education institutions throughout Germany, Europe and North and South America, stand in solidarity with students protesting at the Westend Campus.
In a statement written in German and English, they "reject" the police eviction promoted by the board of directors.
Werner Müller-Estler, president of the university, evicted the building occupied by students and teachers on an educational strike last week because the walls and artworks were covered with propaganda.
As a result, five students were injured.
