New Silicon Valley
For many years, it was considered a secret city, inaccessible to Western visitors.
Selenograd, one of the ten districts of Moscow, was in the Soviet Union a heavily guarded site for secret arms research.
Today, the community of 216,000 inhabitants, located 37 kilometers from the center of Moscow, is considered the "Russian Silicon Valley".
Here are important research and production centers of micro and nanoelectronics.
Since September 2008, representatives of Selenograd have contacted the Riedberg headquarters in Frankfurt, university institutes and companies of the Frankfurt Innovation Centre (FIZ).
Several visits were made to each other and now, on Wednesday, Selenograd and Riedberg sign a “Tight Collaboration Protocol” in Frankfurt.
Deputy Moscow Mayor Juri Rosljak and Selengrad Mayor Anatoly Smirnov led the Russian delegation; for Frankfurt signed the head of planning services Edwin Schwarz.
In 2010 FIZ representatives and directors of small and medium-sized enterprises of the natural sciences research center will travel to a seminar in Selenograd.
Scientific exchange
This is an ongoing scientific exchange.
But it also deals with business relations.
FIZ companies will have the opportunity to set foot in the growing Russian market.
In return, Russian scientific companies want to have access to contracts in Germany.
Selenograd is home to important Russian companies and research institutes.
These include, for example, the Moscow Institute of Electronic Technology, the large Sitronics consortium and Rossijskaja Elektronika.
The community was founded in 1958 as the so-called "Socialist Planning City" for armament research.
Selenograd (literally translated as "Green City") was named after the forested mountain landscape, in which research facilities were established.
Brakes from Stuttgart
The Stuttgart 21 Dimension is not high enough at all.
For the supporters of the project it is simply and plainly "the new heart of Europe".
The S21 law is much more than the reduction of a railway station, more than a monstrous construction project, which will precipitate the capital of the Banden-Württemberg region a decade of chaos of irreparable construction sites.
Stuttgart 21 emerged from the spirit of the 1980s.
Terminals with rails, which end up in the middle of the city, were then considered 19th century engineering fossils, which acted as brakes of modern rail traffic, since in the past it took a huge amount of time to hook the locomotives back and forth.
Roll, stop dry continue the journey; but so it must be done.
And that’s why the terminals had to disappear: in Frankfurt and Munich.
And in Stuttgart: a pass station, which is about halfway between the trans-European lines of operation between Paris and Budapest/Bratislava; hence the slogan of "Heart of Europe".
The S21 will really be started, even though the visions of the 80s are no longer compatible with reality.
Even the most ambitious designers have known that in the Hessian and Bavarian capitals it is almost priceless to implement the reduction.
Railway terminals of course also have no more problems of entry and exit, since there are reversible locomotives with tractor unit and driver's carriage at both ends.
However: Stuttgart 21 including the new built section of ICE towards Ulm will already be started.
Federal and communal politicians have put it that way.
The railway continues, also because the risks of the Republic’s large individual infrastructure projects are carried by the taxpayer and not the state.
From an urban point of view, the project is still justified to some extent.
New urban space is created, provided with many green areas, probably from the designer’s computer-generated graphics.
For the rail transport system the S21 is harmful.
The crossing station and road support are designed for the transport of people, which was attributed to the enormous growth typical of the 1980s.
At that time, there was no competition for low-cost flights.
But modern transport policy must first be concerned with strengthening freight transport, since rail transport is considerably greener than that carried out by trucks on the roads.
However, the new sections under construction are good for freight trains due to the intense gradients.
Even more serious is that the S21 also indirectly affects many other railroad projects.
More than six billion euros must be buried in the Zuavos.
That's the official figure.
Experts consider it to be more realistic between ten and fifteen billion.
It is certain that in the next decade the money will be missing in other narrow crossings and passages on the net.
A total of 60 major projects are on the list of the Ministry of Transport.
One of the most important is the extension of more than 180 kilometers of long rails through the Rhine Valley.
Since 1987, the slow-moving track has been built.
It would be urgent here to step on the accelerator properly.
However, the S21 acts as a brake.
The Rhine Valley section will be the bottleneck for international freight transport: through the heart of Europe.
