Banks in the U.S. are paying back their loans.
The big American banks shaken by the crisis are stripping away their state bonds.
The “Bank of America” gave back at once the aid it had been provided by the bank bailout fund Tarp of a total of 45 billion (approximately 30 billion euros).
The Citi group also plans to return state aid, according to a report by CNBC.
With this the institutes intend to free themselves from the restrictions that had gone hand in hand with the acceptance of the money, such as the limitation on the payment of bonuses to directors, as well as the payment of high fees.
The "Bank of America" had obtained approximately 19 billion cash through convertible bonds.
The rest of the sum was taken from the box itself, which had enough means, among others for the sale of items.
Banking director Kenneth Lewis thanked U.S. taxpayers on Wednesday night: the financial injection helped overcome very difficult times.
The banking house had miscalculated the investment bank’s absorption effort at the climax of the financial crisis.
The Citi group also aims to raise money in the capital market to be able to free itself from its obligations to the state.
CNBC reported from well-known circles that the U.S. bank could announce by Thursday the increase of its capital by 20 billion dollars.
A representative of the Citi Group declined to comment.
