Dreamy worlds
While awake, some people see images and hear voices that others do not see or hear.
It is not only in the case of the mentally ill and the drug addicts that the boundaries between imagination and reality are blurred.
As long as it happens during sleep, everything is in order.
When we are lying in our dark rooms with our eyes closed, we can surrender unhindered to the wildest imaginations and creations of fantasy.
However, anyone who experiences sleep-like states during waking, or sees and hears things that others do not see or hear, is most often considered in the modern Western world as insane or drug addict, or at least as manic.
But such images and voices do not only arise in the mentally ill or in the drugged.
Our imagination is to blame: the same neural processes that allow us to design houses, paint pictures or write novels, sometimes cause the boundaries between sleep, madness and reality to blur.
Dream-modified states of alert consciousness can appear in the most diverse forms, at best we call them visions, and at worst, madness.
Although the triggers and effects can be distinguished, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the psychedelic experiences of the New Age prophet Carlos Castañeda, the states of shamanic possession, and psychoses and hallucinations can be referred to similar processes.
Hallucinations or delusions arise when the balance of neuronal communication substances in the brain has been derailed – especially dopamine, noradrenaline, serotonin and acetylcholine – and the interaction between various parts of the brain is disrupted.
During a schizophrenic psychosis, complex hallucinations and crazy thoughts often occur.
Gravity no longer has power over it.
The relationship between madness and sleep has occupied philosophers and physicians since ancient times.
Aristotle conceived of hallucinations as a form of waking sleep, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, observed in 1861 a "great resemblance of the state of madness to dream states", for Sigmund Freud, the dream was even "a psychosis, with all the dispositions, mad formations, and spejis".
It’s autumn 2001, when Henning T. becomes a comic book figure.
His body is two-dimensional and scandalously colorful.
Gravity no longer has power over it, it is floating near the ceiling of the room.
He feels a kick.
Behind him, figures of demons with wings, with red jerks like blood, deformed, grinding teeth.
They are chasing him, kicking him with heavy, flaming boots, throwing him against the walls, he feels the pains all over his body.
Squeaky, malignant voices resonate from the walls and the radio.
He can no longer stand them, the voices that insult and offend him.
Henning T. pulls two wires from the stereo, ties them together to form a hanging knot, and fixes them on a hook on the ceiling.
He climbs into a horn and puts the knot around his neck.
Jump.
The rope is loose.
“What a lesson for you!” shout the voices in a chorus that blows his eardrums, “Go to the clinic and make them heal you!”
Now, Henning T. is 40 and has experienced six acute psychoses, the last two years ago, the first nearly 20 years ago.
The cause was the LSD.
His diagnosis is schizophrenia-affective-paranoid psychosis, he is also manic-depressive, taking drugs, against depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He has learned to live with his illness, he has been married for three years.
In psychosis I have experienced the most terrible anguish and the deepest despair, he says.
Hallucinations are a cruel reality
Approximately one percent of the population falls ill at least once in the life of schizophrenia; in psychiatric clinics it is treated as the second most common disease after depression.
In an acute schizophrenic psychosis, most of the time those affected can no longer distinguish between the outside and the inside world, and fall into a state of over-excitement that can lead to hallucinations, delusions of grandeur, relationship disorders, or persecution mania.
Especially widespread is the hearing of voices: voices that give orders, comment or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are also common.
The affected person is no longer able to distinguish what is important from what is not, the brain can no longer filter out disturbing signals, the consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like sleep, psychosis also opens the doors to a torrent of ideas and fantasies that come from the deepest layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is subject-centered, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, chief physician of the general psychiatry clinic at Heidelberg University Hospital.
The schizophrenic is at the center of events, everything has a meaning directed at him.
At the same time he enters into a passive role, as in a dream, he feels overwhelmed by events and cannot actively organize them.
This is why schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
In general it is not possible to adjust reality to them, hallucinations are a cruel reality, waking up, impossible.
Having experienced a hallucination once in a lifetime
Unlike in a dream, says Fuchs, "the spatial and sensory structure of reality perceived in psychosis remain in principle as it is."
Paranoid thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, distancing from experience takes place in reality.
For researchers it is still unknown why our brain makes cabriolets.
According to Fuchs, states of emergency can cause anyone to lose contact with reality provisionally.
Not everyone develops a psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic disposition for schizophrenia, but studies in twins have shown that in addition to genes there are also other determinants.
Researchers assume that those affected suffer minimal brain damage.
We suspect that the brain’s neuronal maturity is affected at an early stage of development, such as through a mother’s viral disease during pregnancy, Fuchs explains.
But it remains an unknown how that alteration of the neuronal system occurs, which in addition does not manifest itself at all for many years.
The influence of the environment also plays an important role – stress or a traumatic experience can be the triggers of a psychosis when a previous disposition already exists.
Similarly, hallucinogenic drugs can cause a psychosis, as they interfere with the brain’s transmitting system.
When the brain is warming
The illogical thing about all this is that psychotic people suffer from their hallucinations and take very expensive drugs to get rid of them, while others pay for drugs that allow them to experience some, says psychology professor Erich Kasten of Lübeck.
Perceiving a hallucination as pleasant or not often depends on the point of view.
Kasten has been compiling reports on hallucinations and visions for ten years and has analyzed the results in the book Die unreale Welt in unserem Kopf, published last year.
Hallucinations are among the typical accompanying symptoms of psychosis, but also, surprisingly, of many other diseases.
Among them are, along with psychic disorders such as borderline personality disorder or depressions, often also diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer’s and head-brain trauma.
Surprisingly and under certain conditions, the brains of healthy people also suffer from hallucinations.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, are made up of memories that are normally found repressed.
They arise when the areas of the brain in which sensory perceptions are processed are hyperactive or poorly inhibited; when our brain gets hot, but also when stimuli are lacking.
Drugs can cause this condition in the same way as brain damage or a psychosis.
But also stimulus restriction, stress, love sickness, or other brain states of exception.
