Because visual and acoustic hallucinations are active in the same areas of the brain that also process real impressions and noises, those affected like Sarah K. find it difficult to distinguish between visions and reality. "Every experience," says Kasten, "takes place in the brain, reality projects there.
Hallucinations are just as images that the brain produces, which is why they seem so real.”
Kasten also classifies nighttime fantasies as a form of hallucination.
Hallucinations of healthy people do not differ fundamentally from those of an acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, psychically healthy people are able to recognize their visions as unreal.
Kasten therefore recommends that his patients appreciate his hallucinations as a special skill.
The borderline between sleep and hallucination
In this overly conscious world, imaginary experiences are usually pathologized, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and chief physician of the psychiatry and psychotherapy clinic at the Florence-Nightingale-Krankenhauses hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a hard and painful disease but it also entails something positive and creative – madness is a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has researched so-called oneirism, a special form of consciousness, which is perceived as a dream.
Dream hallucinations are almost very complex and detailed dreams that the person who experiences them considers real and that subsequently cannot differentiate from being awake.
Dream conscious states arise in extreme situations associated with trauma or disease, such as in patients with polyradiculoneuropathy, who experience motor paralysis while being fully conscious.
According to Schmidt-Degenhardt, when a person is threatened by a loss of himself or of the world due to a total and permanent motor disability, it replaces a very dangerous real situation with a world of its own and imaginary that is disengaged from reality.
A form of boundary situation between sleep and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to overcome a situation in reality, a change of world occurs, although the real situation remains present in the imagination.
An intensive way to give meaning and interpretation to an unbearable situation in itself that our own capacity for creation allows us not to sink into the nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory.
Also art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen of Zurich describes his dream experiences in his book Herzenwechsel as a soul-saving action.
He was 49 years old, when his conscience embarked on multi-day trips after heart valve surgery with heart transplant included, while his body was doomed to immobility at the intensive care station.
Claussen immersed himself in a world created by himself and visited strange places of the past: he found himself lying in bed, an elderly man aboard a sanatorium on a train, a robot watching over his health.
