75% of working mothers have had work problems due to their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women of the younger generations who want to be mothers.
This is revealed in the study 'Fecundity and work path of women in Spain', prepared by the CSIC in collaboration with the Institute of Women.
The survey of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 leaves no doubt about this: 75% of working mothers have seen limited opportunities in the workplace due to motherhood.
The study indicates that there are many differences in the beginning of coexistence as a couple and the number of children, depending on whether or not they work and the type of work they do.
Those who do not have an activity outside the home, work part-time, or have a non-stable job, start cohabitation as a couple, advance the first maternity, and have more children.
On the contrary, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, delay coexistence and motherhood, and have fewer offspring.
"Women between 35 and 49 years old with fixed work have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after starting cohabitation, a figure that increases to 4.1 women with fixed jobs have needed more time from their life path to get them, which has led them to postpone the union and the arrival of the children.
In addition, the type of work performed exerts a lot of influence on maternity, although less on the timing of mating," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that differentiates the age of women when they get married and have the first offspring.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education, the higher the age at which they get married and have their first child.
The difference is also between women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49 age group, those with elementary and higher education were first-time mothers at 25.1 and 32.1 on average respectively.
"There is also a further division among women depending on their level of education.
While those who have elementary education marry and have their first child before getting a stable job, those of medium or higher levels reverse this sequence and give priority to obtaining a stable job as a precondition for marriage and the arrival of a child.
