On Dorothy Parker: “One day she got on her knees and prayed, ‘Dear God, please make me stop writing like a woman.’
On his tomb were engraved these verses of Spenser: 'The dream after the effort,/ after the storm the harbor,/ after the rest after the war,/ after life weary please death.'
About Virginia Wolf: "In her luggage she also brought her depressions.
The husband would normally accept her telling him that Edward VII was spying on her among the azaleas or that the birds were singing in Greek.
Never has the case occurred of a man so patient and in love with a neurotic whose literary talent was ahead of his madness.
On Pío Baroja: "What did Martín-Santos do but try to inoculate Joyce in Baroja?
What did Benet try but to pass Baroja for Faulkner's guns?
What did Cela do but abdicate that man’s fame to serve as his own pedestal?”
