Emergency braking assistance is now mandatory
As with anti-lock ABS brakes and ESP stability control, emergency braking assistance systems will have to be a mandatory element in European cars.
In fact, they are already in all new passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest a period of absence is set until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to increase the protection of pedestrians although, by its way of working, it can also help avoid many collisions by reach.
The emergency braking assistant does what it does is increase the pressure on the brakes in case of an emergency, which the system detects by the stepping stone that the driver gives.
But it doesn’t always hold that pressure until the end.
According to a study by car component manufacturer Bosch, a third of the drivers involved in an accident had not stepped on the brake before the collision and half of them did not take full advantage of the force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The aid intervention, on the other hand, requires the maximum of the braking system, reducing the distance that the car takes to stop.
According to a study by the EU itself, if all cars were equipped with such elements, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided per year.
The reduction will be even greater - it is estimated that one in four accidents involving damage to people would be avoided - when so-called intelligent emergency braking systems are popularized.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that (through a radar or a camera) detects obstacles and alerts the driver, in addition to slightly acting on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, it helps by increasing the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
In case it does not react, and even if the collision is inevitable, the device exerts maximum effort to the brakes to minimize damage.
