In these days of storms and accidents, not only car workshops win.
Every day thousands of cars that have suffered a disaster are towed to a workshop, where an expert must evaluate the damage suffered and what the cost of repair will be.
No accident is the same, and calculating parts costs and labor time can be a lengthy and complicated task.
Manually calculate the cost of a repair of between 20,000 and 30,000 euros, including parts and labor, can take two or three hours.
Instead, with the support of the latest computer tools it would be a matter of minutes.
That’s why almost 100% of experts use this type of system.
Service providers and solutions for claims valuation and maintenance are dedicated to collecting the information supplied by manufacturers, then processing it and offering it to their customers in the form of a useful tool.
In Spain, Audatex, of the American group Solera, is the leading firm; 80% of the valuations are made with its products.
The other firms competing in the field of appraisal tools and information processing on the sector are GtMotive and Eurotax.
Working with the data that manufacturers provide is far from straightforward.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, commercial director of Audatex, in Spain they work with 63 manufacturers and importers, and each of them provides them with the information in different formats.
In addition, the amount of data to be processed continues to increase, to the point that in the last five years more versions, variants and engines have been released than in the previous fifteen.
As soon as a new car comes out, these companies get to work.
It is a very difficult task, because you have to catalog each of the thousands of parts of the vehicle and enter its price.
In addition, each model is made a "smart" graphic image where you can "pin" different parts of tourism.
If it’s a windy model, the job can be ready in a week if the process goes very fast.
If it is a minority car, it can take three or four months. Currently, Audatex has complete information about 99.2% of the cars marketed in Spain.
Among the most exclusive models are information about Porsche, but not Ferrari or Lamborghini, for example.
As for the mobile park that circulates, they exceed 99%.
To carry out the documentation work and the elaboration of the databases, Audatex has eight centers spread around the world (Spain, France, Germany, USA, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan), and each of them specializes in specific brands.
The national headquarters is in Alcobendas (Madrid).
There, more than a hundred technicians (usually mechanics experts) work simultaneously with three computer screens.
Audatex invests 90 million euros annually in developing these databases.
Every month, 2.5 million pieces of data are included, and customers receive updates every other day.
The elaboration of that huge flow of information allows these companies to give them different uses and offer various products.
